		<!-- message -->
		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px ">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <font color="#8A949A">..::</font> <span class="smallfont">Quoting Shylodog <font color="#8A949A">::..</font></span><br />
	<span style="color: #BFAD97"><br />
<br />
At this time, I feel that my bloodlust and need for retalitation has been sated. I think we've killed enough insurgents and civilians to fill my personal quota for those who were lost during the 9/11 tragedy. I also feel that the money we're pouring into Iraq to &quot;Rebuild&quot; would be much better applied to security back home.<br />
<br />
</span><br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <font color="#8A949A">..::</font> <span class="smallfont">End Quote</span><font color="#8A949A"> ::..</font>
</div>
<br />
I don't mean to pick on you, Shy, but I'm afraid that this is exactly what many people will start to think in the coming year or two, and it's dangerous territory.<br />
<br />
The battle cry right now is the &quot;War on Terror&quot; with the subtitle &quot;Bringing Freedom to Iraq&quot;, and plenty of people believe it... for now.  Once their fervor settles, people are going to start wondering why we're spending all this money on a foreign country.  When the news isn't all images of our boys mowing down opposition forces and routing terrorist cells, Americans will get bored. A bored America isn't one that will support the rebuilding of Iraq.  It's much more fun to spend money on kicking ass than it is to fund relief efforts and nation building.<br />
<br />
So then what happens?  Support dwindles, the next administration hustles our forces out of the region, the UN takes over, and it settles back into just another unsettled state in the Middle East...<br />
<br />
So assuming that I'm right... what will we have accomplished?</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
